Looks good. Now let me also look at what happens when Engine update is checking for the `'idle'` condition with `pendingTalkTarget`. There's a potential issue: when A has been walking to B's location with `pendingTalkTarget` set, and A arrives (action becomes `'idle'`), `_handleTalkArrival` is called. But there's also `_handleObjectArrival` check. Let me make sure these don't conflict.

Looking at the code: 
```js
// Handle arrival: character reached target object tile
if (char.action === 'idle' && char.targetObjectId) {
  this._handleObjectArrival(char);
}

// Handle arrival: character reached talk target
if (char.action === 'idle' && char.pendingTalkTarget) {
  this._handleTalkArrival(char);
}
```

If both `targetObjectId` and `pendingTalkTarget` are set simultaneously (which shouldn't happen since they're mutually exclusive), the object arrival handler runs first, but then `startTalk` clears `targetObjectId` anyway, so there's no actual conflict.

Actually, I need to reconsider the order here. When `_handleTalkArrival` runs and calls `startTalk`, it clears `targetObjectId` — but `_handleObjectArrival` already executed before that point, so the clearing happens after. The real question is whether `targetObjectId` can even be set while `pendingTalkTarget` is active. Looking at the `talk` decision in AIEngine, it doesn't clear `targetObjectId`, so I should verify if that's actually a problem. Looking at the `talk` case in AIEngine, I notice I'm not clearing `targetObjectId` when a character decides to talk to another character. In the `interact` case, this gets properly released when switching targets, but the `talk` case skips this step. This creates a bug where if a character is already walking to an object and then the AI decides to talk instead, both `targetObjectId` and `pendingTalkTarget` end up set, causing both arrival handlers to potentially fire. I need to add the same object reservation cleanup that `move` and `interact` cases already do.

